>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbde738539_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Chá»£ Ä�&agrave; Láº¡t vá»� Ä‘&ecirc;m<br /></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">H&agrave;ng trÄƒm nÄƒm trÆ°á»›c Ä‘&acirc;y, Ä�&agrave; Láº¡t l&agrave; Ä‘á»‹a b&agrave;n cÆ° tr&uacute; cá»§a ngÆ°á»�i Láº¡ch, vá»‘n l&agrave; cÆ° d&acirc;n cá»§a to&agrave;n bá»™ cao nguy&ecirc;n Lang Biang. Ä�&agrave; Láº¡t c&oacute; diá»‡n t&iacute;ch hÆ¡n 400 km&sup2;, bao bá»�c bá»Ÿi c&aacute;c Ä‘á»‰nh n&uacute;i cao v&agrave; d&atilde;y n&uacute;i li&ecirc;n tiáº¿p:<br /> <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ph&iacute;a Báº¯c v&agrave; T&acirc;y Báº¯c giá»›i háº¡n bá»Ÿi d&atilde;y ChorÆ¡mui, Yá»™ Ä�a Myut (1.816 m), T&acirc;y Báº¯c dá»±a v&agrave;o ch&acirc;n d&atilde;y n&uacute;i ChÆ° Yang Kae (1.921 m), thuá»™c quáº§n sÆ¡n Lang Biang m&agrave; Ä‘á»‰nh cao nháº¥t l&agrave; ChÆ° Yang Sinh (1.408 m).<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ph&iacute;a Ä�&ocirc;ng l&agrave; ch&acirc;n d&atilde;y n&uacute;i Bi Doup (2.278 m) dá»‘c xuá»‘ng cao nguy&ecirc;n Dran.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ph&iacute;a Ä�&ocirc;ng Nam cháº¯n bá»Ÿi d&atilde;y Cho Proline (1.629 m).<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ph&iacute;a Nam v&agrave; T&acirc;y Nam c&oacute; d&atilde;y n&uacute;i Voi (1.754 m) v&agrave; Y&agrave;ng SÆ¡reng bao bá»�c.</p>','Wikipedia','','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_square.jpeg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_thumbnail.jpeg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_small.jpeg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_crop.jpeg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_medium.jpeg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cbd8c1bde4_large.jpeg','active',2,'2010-08-31 15:37:17',1,'admin','2010-08-31 15:43:30',1,'admin',1,'admin','2010-08-31 15:37:38',0,0,0,0,NULL,0,'vi_VN'),(23,2,'Colled cake','','colled-cake','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n (literally \"rolled cake\") is a dish from northern Vietnam.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a cr&ecirc;pe-like roll made from a thin, wide sheet of rice flour filled with ground pork, minced wood ear mushroom, and other ingredients. Sides for this dish usually consist of cháº£ lá»¥a (Vietnamese pork sausage) and bean sprouts, with the dipping sauce called nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m. Sometimes, a drop of c&agrave; cuá»‘ng, which is the essence of a giant water bug, Lethocerus indicus, is added to the nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m for extra flavor, although this ingredient is scarce and quite expensive.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37ba9053_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"207\" height=\"155\" /> <img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37d048e1_small.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"207\" height=\"155\" /> <img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37e5c955_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"238\" height=\"154\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Unlike shahe fen, the rice sheet in b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n is extremely thin and delicate. It is a light dish, and is generally eaten for breakfast everywhere in Vietnam. A different version of b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n, called b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; and b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh, may be found in Thanh Tr&igrave;, a southern district of Hanoi and K&ecirc;nh village of Nam Ä�á»‹nh, an ancient village in the centre of Nam Ä�á»‹nh city.B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; or B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh are not rolls, but just rice sheets eaten with cháº£ lá»¥a, fried shallots, or prawns; see the article B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n in the Vietnamese Wikipedia.<br /><br />A similar Chinese dish is the Cantonese dish coeng4 fan2 (è‚ ç²‰; pinyin: ch&aacute;ngfÄ›n), usually translated into English as \"steamed rice roll\" or \"rice noodle roll,\" which is a form of dim sum.</p>','Wikipedia','','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_square.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_thumbnail.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_small.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_crop.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_medium.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_large.jpg','active',2,'2010-08-31 15:59:15',1,'admin','2010-08-31 16:03:19',1,'admin',1,'admin','2010-08-31 15:59:26',0,0,0,0,NULL,0,'en_US'),(24,17,'BÃ¡nh cuá»‘n','','banh-cuon','<p>B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n hay b&aacute;nh Æ°á»›t l&agrave; loáº¡i b&aacute;nh l&agrave;m tá»« bá»™t gáº¡o háº¥p tr&aacute;ng má»�ng, Ä‘á»ƒ Äƒn khi c&ograve;n Æ°á»›t, trong c&oacute; thá»ƒ cuá»‘n nh&acirc;n hoáº·c kh&ocirc;ng nh&acirc;n (kh&aacute;c vá»›i b&aacute;nh tr&aacute;ng, (b&aacute;nh Ä‘a) pháº£i phÆ¡i kh&ocirc;; hay b&aacute;nh Æ°á»›t á»Ÿ miá»�n Nam. B&aacute;nh thÆ°á»�ng Äƒn vá»›i má»™t loáº¡i nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m pha nháº¡t tá»« nÆ°á»›c máº¯m v&agrave; náº¿u l&agrave; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n truyá»�n thá»‘ng th&igrave; kh&ocirc;ng thá»ƒ thiáº¿u tinh dáº§u c&agrave; cuá»‘ng pha trong nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m khi Äƒn thÆ°á»�ng k&egrave;m th&ecirc;m cháº£ lá»£n.</p>','<h2>C&aacute;ch l&agrave;m</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Gáº¡o ngon, xay má»‹n, h&ograve;a vá»›i nÆ°á»›c. Ä�áº·t ná»“i háº¥p, cÄƒng váº£i má»�ng tr&ecirc;n miá»‡ng ná»“i. Má»—i láº§n cho má»™t mu&ocirc;i bá»™t nhá»�. xoa Ä‘á»�u l&ecirc;n bá»� máº·t miáº¿ng váº£i Ä‘á»ƒ l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c má»�ng, c&oacute; thá»ƒ thoa th&ecirc;m ch&uacute;t má»¡ Ä‘á»ƒ dá»… láº¥y ra.<br /><br />Sau khi b&aacute;nh ch&iacute;n, d&ugrave;ng Ä‘Å©a to hoáº·c thanh tre gáº¡t ra Ä‘Ä©a, l&uacute;c n&agrave;y c&oacute; thá»ƒ cuá»™n th&ecirc;m nh&acirc;n gá»“m má»™t &iacute;t thá»‹t vai ná»­a náº¡c ná»­a má»¡, t&ocirc;m, bÄƒm c&ugrave;ng má»™c nhÄ©, náº¥m hÆ°Æ¡ng Ä‘&atilde; x&agrave;o ch&iacute;n vá»›i c&aacute;c gia vá»‹ nhÆ° máº¯m, háº¡t ti&ecirc;u... Ráº¯c th&ecirc;m h&agrave;nh kh&ocirc; phi thÆ¡m v&agrave; d&ugrave;ng vá»›i nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m Ä‘á»§ c&aacute;c vá»‹ chua, cay, máº·n, ngá»�t.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37ba9053_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"207\" height=\"155\" /> <img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37d048e1_small.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"207\" height=\"155\" /> <img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37e5c955_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"238\" height=\"154\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave;</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; l&agrave; m&oacute;n Äƒn ná»•i tiáº¿ng cá»§a ngÆ°á»�i H&agrave; Ná»™i, l&agrave; Ä‘áº·c sáº£n cá»§a phÆ°á»�ng Thanh Tr&igrave;, Quáº­n Ho&agrave;ng Mai, H&agrave; Ná»™i. B&aacute;nh Ä‘Æ°á»£c l&agrave;m tá»« gáº¡o gi&eacute; c&aacute;nh, t&aacute;m thÆ¡m, tr&aacute;ng má»�ng nhÆ° tá»� giáº¥y.<br /><br />B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; kh&ocirc;ng c&oacute; nh&acirc;n, thÆ°á»�ng Ä‘Æ°á»£c xáº¿p th&agrave;nh tá»«ng lá»›p trong l&ograve;ng má»™t chiáº¿c th&uacute;ng, tr&ecirc;n phá»§ tá»� l&aacute; sen hay l&aacute; chuá»‘i, l&aacute; dong. NgÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n b&aacute;nh thÆ°á»�ng Ä‘á»™i th&uacute;ng b&aacute;nh tr&ecirc;n Ä‘áº§u, di dáº¡o b&aacute;n tr&ecirc;n phá»‘ phÆ°á»�ng H&agrave; Ná»™i. Khi gáº·p ngÆ°á»�i mua, ngÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n h&agrave;ng sáº½ háº¡ th&uacute;ng xuá»‘ng, láº§n giá»Ÿ tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n má»�ng, t&aacute;ch tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh sao l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n khá»�i bá»‹ r&aacute;ch. Tr&ecirc;n máº·t l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘iá»ƒm nhá»¯ng cá»�ng h&agrave;nh l&aacute; m&agrave;u v&agrave;ng, n&acirc;u Ä‘&atilde; Ä‘Æ°á»£c phi qua tr&ecirc;n cháº£o. Má»—i lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘&oacute; sáº½ Ä‘Æ°á»£c sáº¯p xáº¿p gá»�n láº¡i tr&ecirc;n Ä‘Ä©a, láº§n lÆ°á»£t tá»«ng miáº¿ng b&aacute;nh má»™t Ä‘Æ°á»£c Ä‘áº·t cáº¡nh nhau. Sau Ä‘&oacute;, vá»›i má»™t nh&aacute;t k&eacute;o, táº¥t cáº£ c&aacute;c l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c cáº¯t Ä‘&ocirc;i. C&ocirc;ng viá»‡c tiáº¿p theo l&agrave; nháº¥c má»™t ná»­a Ä‘áº§u b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n má»›i cáº¯t Ä‘&oacute;, Ä‘áº·t l&ecirc;n tr&ecirc;n ná»­a kia Ä‘á»ƒ ngÆ°á»�i thÆ°á»Ÿng thá»©c c&oacute; thá»ƒ nh&igrave;n tháº¥y r&otilde; tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n tr&aacute;ng má»�ng nhÆ° giáº¥y. B&aacute;nh Ä‘Æ°á»£c Äƒn vá»›i thá»© nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m Ä‘áº·c trÆ°ng cho tá»«ng ngÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n b&aacute;nh ri&ecirc;ng, c&oacute; thá»ƒ Äƒn k&egrave;m cháº£ quáº¿, gi&ograve; lá»¥a hoáº·c Ä‘áº­u r&aacute;n v&agrave; rau m&ugrave;i.</p>','Wikipedia','','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_square.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_thumbnail.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_small.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_crop.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_medium.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc45c523c6_large.jpg','active',2,'2010-08-31 16:08:32',1,'admin','2010-08-31 16:09:18',1,'admin',1,'admin','2010-08-31 16:08:52',0,0,0,0,NULL,0,'vi_VN'),(25,7,'Phá»Ÿ&nbsp;','','pho','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Phá»Ÿ (Vietnamese pronunciation: often written pho in Australia, New Zealand, United Kingdom, and United States where it is typically pronounced /ËˆfÊŒ/) is a Vietnamese noodle soup, usually served with beef (pho bo) or chicken (pho ga). The soup includes noodles made from rice and is often served with basil, lime, bean sprouts, and peppers that are added to the soup by the consumer.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The origin of phá»Ÿ is uncertain, and is mostly culled from oral histories. The specific place of origin appears to be southwest of Hanoi in Nam Dinh province, believed to harbor both a Chinese and French connection. The noodles comes from China, and the broth appears to be French in origin, making use of bones and lesser cuts of beef. Some have suggested that phá»Ÿ is derived from pot au feu, the classic French beef stew. Phá»Ÿ did not become popular in South Vietnam until the mid-1950s. Linguistically, however, this is unlikely. In the Vietnamese language, the word phá»Ÿ carries a non-flat category, whereas most French loanwords carry a flat tone, sáº¯c or náº·ng tone, depending on the end consonant except the loanwords are ended with -t, -p, -c, -ch consonants. Phá»Ÿ does not match this rule.<br />a plain Cantonese Hofan</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79c58b72_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>a plain Cantonese Hofan</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Some observers believe phá»Ÿ may come from the Cantonese rice vermicelli Hofan (æ²³ç²‰) which are interchangeably abbreviated as either fan2(ç²‰, pháº¥n in Tá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t) or Ho2(æ²³, H&agrave; inTá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t ), the two sounds giving the name \"phá»Ÿ\".Both fan and pho refer to the same rice noodles found in Vietnam and Guangdong, China, suggesting that rice noodles may have been brought to Vietnam by Cantonese immigrants from the Guangdong province in the early 20th century. The noodles are cooked identically in both places, and are often seasoned using fish sauce, garnished with bean sprouts, and served with meat balls and sliced beef. Vietnamese phá»Ÿ, however, is further garnished with fresh mint, cilantro, basil, bean sprouts, limes, sliced chili peppers and sliced raw beef[9]; this is especially true of Saigon-style phá»Ÿ. Furthermore, the broth of phá»Ÿ is made of beef bones and fresh onion, whereas the Cantonese broth of fan is made of dried flatfish and other seafood. In some regional varieties, the Vietnamese broth may also have a mildly sweet flavour from Asian yellow rock sugar, but the Cantonese version is not.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Vietnamese phá»Ÿ noodle soup with sliced rare beef and well done beef brisket<br />Possibly the earliest reference to phá»Ÿ in English was in the book Recipes of All Nations edited by Countess Morphy in 1935. In the book, phá»Ÿ is described as \"an Annamese soup held in high esteem...made with beef, a veal bone, onions, a bayleaf, salt, and pepper, and a small teaspoon of nuoc-man.\"<br /><br />With the Vietnam war and the victory of the Viet Cong, phá»Ÿ was brought to many countries by Vietnamese refugees fleeing Vietnam from the 1970s onwards. It is especially popular in large cities with substantial Vietnamese populations and enclaves such as Paris in France, the West Coast of Canada[10], the East and West Coast of the United States, Sydney and Melbourne of Australia, and Hong Kong.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79d3600b_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Typical garnishes for phá»Ÿ: cilantro, basil, lime, bean sprouts and onions.</em></p>','Wikipedia','','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc85f10dc6_square.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc85f10dc6_thumbnail.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc85f10dc6_small.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc85f10dc6_crop.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc85f10dc6_medium.jpg','http://localhost/amancms/upload