xuy&ecirc;n ná»•i l&ecirc;n Ä‘á»ƒ thá»Ÿ. Trong Ä‘á»�n Ngá»�c SÆ¡n c&oacute; trÆ°ng b&agrave;y ti&ecirc;u báº£n má»™t c&aacute; thá»ƒ r&ugrave;a Há»“ GÆ°Æ¡m. H&igrave;nh áº£nh cá»§a r&ugrave;a cÅ©ng gáº¯n liá»�n vá»›i há»“, th&ocirc;ng qua t&ecirc;n gá»�i th&aacute;p R&ugrave;a á»Ÿ giá»¯a há»“ v&agrave; truyá»�n thuyáº¿t L&ecirc; Lá»£i tráº£ gÆ°Æ¡m cho tháº§n Kim Quy, má»™t truyá»�n thuyáº¿t mang láº¡i t&ecirc;n gá»�i cho báº£n th&acirc;n há»“. C&aacute;c nh&agrave; khoa há»�c váº«n Ä‘ang tiáº¿p tá»¥c nghi&ecirc;n cá»©u Ä‘á»ƒ t&igrave;m ra Ä‘Æ°á»£c ch&iacute;nh x&aacute;c ph&acirc;n loáº¡i cá»§a r&ugrave;a Há»“ GÆ°Æ¡m.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 12:03:39',1,'admin'),(15,5,1,'Sa Pa','','sa-pa','<p>Sapa is a frontier town and capital of Sa Pa District in the L&agrave;o Cai province in northwest Vietnam. It is one of the main market towns in the area, where many ethnic minority groups such as H\'mong, Dao and Tay live.</p>','<p>Sa Pa District is located in Lao Cai Province, north-west Vietnam, and 350 km north-west of Hanoi, close to the border with China. The Hoang Lien Son range of mountains dominates the district, which is at the eastern extremity of the Himalayas. This range includes Vietnam\'s highest mountain, Fan Si Pan, at a height of 3142m above sea level. The town of Sa Pa lies at an altitude of about 1600 m. The climate is moderate and rainy in summer (May&mdash;August), and foggy and cold with occasional snowfalls in winter.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7c9d36eeb3f_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Sa Pa town</em></p>\r\n<p>Sa Pa is a quiet mountain town and home to a great diversity of ethnic minority peoples. The total population of 36,000 consists mostly of minority groups. Besides the Kinh (Viet) people (15%) there are mainly 5 ethnic groups in Sapa: Hmong 52%, Dao 25%, Tay 5%, Giay 2% and a small number of Xa Pho. Approximately 7,000 live in Sapa, the other 36,000 being scattered in small communes throughout the district.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7c9de6e9139_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>View on the mountains from downtown Sapa</em></p>\r\n<p>Most of the ethnic minority people work their land on sloping terraces since the vast majority of the land is mountainous. Their staple foods are rice and corn. Rice, by its very nature of being a labour intensive crop, makes the daily fight for survival paramount. The unique climate in Sapa has a major influence on the ethnic minorities who live in the area. With sub-tropical summers, temperate winters and 160 days of mist annually, the influence on agricultural yields and health related issues are significant.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 13:16:01',1,'admin'),(16,6,13,'Sa Pa','','sa-pa','<p>Sa Pa l&agrave; má»™t thá»‹ tráº¥n v&agrave; cÅ©ng l&agrave; má»™t khu nghá»‰ m&aacute;t ná»•i tiáº¿ng thuá»™c huyá»‡n Sa Pa, tá»‰nh L&agrave;o Cai, Viá»‡t Nam.</p>','<p>Náº±m á»Ÿ ph&iacute;a T&acirc;y Báº¯c cá»§a Viá»‡t Nam, thá»‹ tráº¥n Sa Pa á»Ÿ Ä‘á»™ cao 1.600 m&eacute;t so vá»›i má»±c nÆ°á»›c biá»ƒn, c&aacute;ch th&agrave;nh phá»‘ L&agrave;o Cai 38 km v&agrave; 376 km t&iacute;nh tá»« H&agrave; Ná»™i. Ngo&agrave;i con Ä‘Æ°á»�ng ch&iacute;nh tá»« th&agrave;nh phá»‘ L&agrave;o Cai, Ä‘á»ƒ tá»›i Sa Pa c&ograve;n má»™t tuyáº¿n giao th&ocirc;ng kh&aacute;c, quá»‘c lá»™ 4D ná»‘i tá»« x&atilde; B&igrave;nh LÆ°, Lai Ch&acirc;u. Máº·c d&ugrave; pháº§n lá»›n cÆ° d&acirc;n huyá»‡n Sa Pa l&agrave; nhá»¯ng ngÆ°á»�i d&acirc;n tá»™c thiá»ƒu sá»‘, nhÆ°ng thá»‹ tráº¥n láº¡i táº­p trung chá»§ yáº¿u nhá»¯ng ngÆ°á»�i Kinh sinh sá»‘ng báº±ng n&ocirc;ng nghiá»‡p v&agrave; dá»‹ch vá»¥ du lá»‹ch.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7c9f51795a3_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Ruá»™ng báº­c thang</em></p>\r\n<p>Sa Pa c&oacute; kh&iacute; háº­u mang sáº¯c th&aacute;i &ocirc;n Ä‘á»›i v&agrave; cáº­n nhiá»‡t Ä‘á»›i, kh&ocirc;ng kh&iacute; m&aacute;t máº» quanh nÄƒm. Thá»�i tiáº¿t á»Ÿ thá»‹ tráº¥n má»™t ng&agrave;y c&oacute; Ä‘á»§ bá»‘n m&ugrave;a: buá»•i s&aacute;ng l&agrave; tiáº¿t trá»�i m&ugrave;a xu&acirc;n, buá»•i trÆ°a tiáº¿t trá»�i nhÆ° v&agrave;o háº¡, thÆ°á»�ng c&oacute; náº¯ng nháº¹, kh&iacute; háº­u dá»‹u m&aacute;t, buá»•i chiá»�u m&acirc;y v&agrave; sÆ°Æ¡ng rÆ¡i xuá»‘ng táº¡o cáº£m gi&aacute;c l&agrave;nh láº¡nh nhÆ° trá»�i thu v&agrave; ban Ä‘&ecirc;m l&agrave; c&aacute;i r&eacute;t cá»§a m&ugrave;a Ä‘&ocirc;ng. Nhiá»‡t Ä‘á»™ kh&ocirc;ng kh&iacute; trung b&igrave;nh nÄƒm cá»§a Sa Pa l&agrave; 15 &deg;C. M&ugrave;a h&egrave;, thá»‹ tráº¥n kh&ocirc;ng pháº£i chá»‹u c&aacute;i náº¯ng gay gáº¯t nhÆ° v&ugrave;ng Ä‘á»“ng báº±ng ven biá»ƒn, khoáº£ng 13 &deg;C &ndash; 15 &deg;C v&agrave;o ban Ä‘&ecirc;m v&agrave; 20 &deg;C &ndash; 25 &deg;C v&agrave;o ban ng&agrave;y. M&ugrave;a Ä‘&ocirc;ng thÆ°á»�ng c&oacute; m&acirc;y m&ugrave; bao phá»§ v&agrave; láº¡nh, nhiá»‡t Ä‘á»™ c&oacute; khi xuá»‘ng dÆ°á»›i 0 &deg;C, Ä‘&ocirc;i khi c&oacute; tuyáº¿t rÆ¡i. LÆ°á»£ng mÆ°a trung b&igrave;nh h&agrave;ng nÄƒm á»Ÿ Ä‘&acirc;y khoáº£ng tá»« 1.800 Ä‘áº¿n 2.200 mm, táº­p trung nhiá»�u nháº¥t v&agrave;o khoáº£ng thá»�i gian tá»« th&aacute;ng 5 tá»›i th&aacute;ng 8</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7c9ee47d19c_medium.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Nh&agrave; thá»� Ä‘&aacute; táº¡i Sa Pa</em></p>\r\n<p>Thá»‹ tráº¥n Sa Pa l&agrave; má»™t trong nhá»¯ng nÆ¡i hiáº¿m hoi cá»§a Viá»‡t Nam c&oacute; tuyáº¿t. Trong khoáº£ng thá»�i gian tá»« 1971 tá»›i 2008, 14 láº§n tuyáº¿t rÆ¡i táº¡i Sa Pa. Láº§n tuyáº¿t rÆ¡i máº¡nh nháº¥t v&agrave;o ng&agrave;y 13 th&aacute;ng 2 nÄƒm 1968, li&ecirc;n tá»¥c tá»« 3 giá»� s&aacute;ng Ä‘áº¿n 14 giá»� c&ugrave;ng ng&agrave;y, d&agrave;y tá»›i 20 cm.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 13:21:29',1,'admin'),(17,7,5,'Perfume River','','perfume-river','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>The Perfume River</strong> (Vietnamese: S&ocirc;ng HÆ°Æ¡ng or HÆ°Æ¡ng Giang; H&aacute;n n&ocirc;m: é¦™æ±Ÿ) is a river that crosses the city of Huáº¿, in the central Vietnamese province of Thá»«a Thi&ecirc;n Huáº¿.</p>','<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">Etymology</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the autumn, flowers from orchards upriver from Huáº¿ fall into the water, giving the river a perfume-like aroma.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ca04e32d9f_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>HÆ°Æ¡ng River in Huáº¿</em></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">Source and flow</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Perfume River has two sources, both of which begin in the D&atilde;y TrÆ°á»�ng SÆ¡n mountain range and meet at Bang Lang Fork. The Ta Trach (Left Tributary) originates in the Truong Dong mountains and flows northwest towards Bang Lang Fork. The shorter Huu Trach (Right Tributary) flows past the Tuan ferry landing towards Bang Lang Fork.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The river then flows in south-north direction past the temples of Hon Chen and Ngoc Tran and then turns north-west, meandering through the Nguyet Bieu and Luong Quan plains. Continuing on, the Huong River then flows to the north-east to Huáº¿ city, only an echo of Truong Son mountain, and passes the resting place of Nguyen emperors. The river of green water continues its itinerary, passing Hen Islet and various villages, crossing the Sinh junction, which is known as the capital of ancient Chau Hoa, before emptying into the Tam Giang Lagoon.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">From Bang Lang to Thuan An estuary, the Perfume River is 30 km long and runs very slowly (as the river level is not much above sea level). The Perfume River darkens as it winds along the foot of Ngoc Tran Mountain - home of the Jade Cup Temple - where there is a very deep abyss.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The river snakes through the villages of Kim Long, Nguyet Bieu, Vy Da, Dong Ba, Gia Hoi, the Dinh market, Nam Pho, Bao Vinh, and through Huáº¿.</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">Life around the river</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The locals who live beside the river in Huáº¿ are often very poor and wash their clothes and bathe in the water. Also, they earn money by dredging the river bed for sand. This sand is collected and then sold to cement manufacturers for a tiny price.</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span id=\"Surrounding_area\" class=\"mw-headline\">Surrounding area</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The 105m Ngu Binh Mountain has a striking and symmetric figure. On both sides of the Even Mount (Bang Son) are 2 small mounts called Ta Bat Son (Left Mount) and Huu Bat Son (Right Mount). After observing that Bang Son resembled a screen, the Nguyá»…n Dynasty decided to build up Huáº¿ which became known as their \"Forbidden Purple City.\" Emperor Gia Long approved the design of geomancers which chose this mount as a front altar of the imposing and solid defending wall system, and renamed it Ngu Binh.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 13:28:27',1,'admin'),(18,8,0,'SÃ´ng HÆ°Æ¡ng','','song-huong','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>S&ocirc;ng HÆ°Æ¡ng </strong>hay HÆ°Æ¡ng Giang (H&aacute;n N&ocirc;m é¦™æ±Ÿ) l&agrave; con s&ocirc;ng cháº£y qua th&agrave;nh phá»‘ Huáº¿ á»Ÿ tá»‰nh Thá»«a Thi&ecirc;n-Huáº¿, miá»�n Trung Viá»‡t Nam.</p>','<h2><span id=\".C4.90.E1.BB.8Ba_l.C3.BD\" class=\"mw-headline\">Ä�á»‹a l&yacute;</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">S&ocirc;ng HÆ°Æ¡ng c&oacute; hai nguá»“n ch&iacute;nh v&agrave; Ä‘á»�u báº¯t nguá»“n tá»« d&atilde;y n&uacute;i TrÆ°á»�ng SÆ¡n. D&ograve;ng ch&iacu