by the legend of Lang Li&ecirc;u, a prince of the sixth H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng, who became H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng\'s successor thank to his creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y, which symbolized respectively the Earth and the Sky. Considered an essential element of the family altar on the occasion of Táº¿t, the making and eating b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng during this time is a well-preserved tradition of Vietnamese people. Beside the Táº¿t holiday, b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng is also tasted all year round as a delicacy of Vietnamese cuisine and one of the national dishes of Vietnam besides nem r&aacute;n and phá»Ÿ.</p>','<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span id=\"Legend_and_symbol\" class=\"mw-headline\">Legend and symbol</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to the book LÄ©nh Nam ch&iacute;ch qu&aacute;i (Extraordinary stories of LÄ©nh Nam) published in 1695, the creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng was credited to Lang Li&ecirc;u, a prince of the sixth H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng. It was said that after the victory against the army of Shang Dynasty, in choosing a successor among his sons, H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng decided to carry out a competition in which each prince brought a delicacy representing the sincerity for the ancestors on the occasion of the Táº¿t, whoever could introduce the most delicious dish for the altar would become the next ruler of the country. While other princes tried to find the rare and delicious foods from forest and sea, the eighteenth prince Lang Li&ecirc;u, who was the poorest son of H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng, could not afford those luxury dishes and had to content with the everyday ingredients ingredients such as rice or pork. Finally, he created one cake in the square form of earth called b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and one in the round form of sky called b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y from these simple ingredients. In tasting the dishes offered by his son, H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng found b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y not only delicious but also a fine respresentation of the respect for ancestors. Therefore he decided to cede the throne to Lang Li&ecirc;u and b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng, b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y became traditional foods during the Táº¿t.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 14:10:47',1,'admin'),(30,11,9,'Steamed cake','','steamed-cake','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh chÆ°ng (steamed cake) is a traditional Vietnamese cake which is made from glutinous rice, mung bean, pork and other ingredients. Its origin is told by the legend of Lang Li&ecirc;u, a prince of the sixth H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng, who became H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng\'s successor thank to his creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y, which symbolized respectively the Earth and the Sky. Considered an essential element of the family altar on the occasion of Táº¿t, the making and eating b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng during this time is a well-preserved tradition of Vietnamese people. Beside the Táº¿t holiday, b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng is also tasted all year round as a delicacy of Vietnamese cuisine and one of the national dishes of Vietnam besides nem r&aacute;n and phá»Ÿ.</p>','<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span id=\"Legend_and_symbol\" class=\"mw-headline\">Legend and symbol</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to the book LÄ©nh Nam ch&iacute;ch qu&aacute;i (Extraordinary stories of LÄ©nh Nam) published in 1695, the creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng was credited to Lang Li&ecirc;u, a prince of the sixth H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng. It was said that after the victory against the army of Shang Dynasty, in choosing a successor among his sons, H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng decided to carry out a competition in which each prince brought a delicacy representing the sincerity for the ancestors on the occasion of the Táº¿t, whoever could introduce the most delicious dish for the altar would become the next ruler of the country. While other princes tried to find the rare and delicious foods from forest and sea, the eighteenth prince Lang Li&ecirc;u, who was the poorest son of H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng, could not afford those luxury dishes and had to content with the everyday ingredients ingredients such as rice or pork. Finally, he created one cake in the square form of earth called b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and one in the round form of sky called b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y from these simple ingredients. In tasting the dishes offered by his son, H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng found b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y not only delicious but also a fine respresentation of the respect for ancestors. Therefore he decided to cede the throne to Lang Li&ecirc;u and b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng, b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y became traditional foods during the Táº¿t.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 14:13:41',1,'admin'),(31,11,9,'Steamed cake','','steamed-cake','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh chÆ°ng (steamed cake) is a traditional Vietnamese cake which is made from glutinous rice, mung bean, pork and other ingredients. Its origin is told by the legend of Lang Li&ecirc;u, a prince of the sixth H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng, who became H&ugrave;ng VÆ°Æ¡ng\'s successor thank to his creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng and b&aacute;nh d&agrave;y, which symbolized respectively the Earth and the Sky. Considered an essential element of the family altar on the occasion of Táº¿t, the making and eating b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng during this time is a well-preserved tradition of Vietnamese people. Beside the Táº¿t holiday, b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng is also tasted all year round as a delicacy of Vietnamese cuisine and one of the national dishes of Vietnam besides nem r&aacute;n and phá»Ÿ.</p>','<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span id=\"Legend_and_symbol\" class=\"mw-headline\">Legend and symbol</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to the book LÄ©nh Nam ch&iacute;ch qu&aacute;i (Extraordinary stories of LÄ©nh Nam) published in 1695, the creation of b&aacute;nh chÆ°ng was credited to Lang Li&ecirc;u, a