r filled with ground pork, minced wood ear mushroom, and other ingredients. Sides for this dish usually consist of cháº£ lá»¥a (Vietnamese pork sausage) and bean sprouts, with the dipping sauce called nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m. Sometimes, a drop of c&agrave; cuá»‘ng, which is the essence of a giant water bug, Lethocerus indicus, is added to the nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m for extra flavor, although this ingredient is scarce and quite expensive.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37ba9053_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" /> <img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37d048e1_small.JPG\" alt=\"\" /> <img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc37e5c955_small.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Unlike shahe fen, the rice sheet in b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n is extremely thin and delicate. It is a light dish, and is generally eaten for breakfast everywhere in Vietnam. A different version of b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n, called b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; and b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh, may be found in Thanh Tr&igrave;, a southern district of Hanoi and K&ecirc;nh village of Nam Ä�á»‹nh, an ancient village in the centre of Nam Ä�á»‹nh city.B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Thanh Tr&igrave; or B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n l&agrave;ng K&ecirc;nh are not rolls, but just rice sheets eaten with cháº£ lá»¥a, fried shallots, or prawns; see the article B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n in the Vietnamese Wikipedia.<br /><br />A similar Chinese dish is the Cantonese dish coeng4 fan2 (è‚ ç²‰; pinyin: ch&aacute;ngfÄ›n), usually translated into English as \"steamed rice roll\" or \"rice noodle roll,\" which is a form of dim sum.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 15:59:15',1,'admin'),(76,23,2,'Colled cake','','colled-cake','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh cuá»‘n (literally \"rolled cake\") is a dish from northern Vietnam.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is a cr&ecirc;pe-like roll made from a thin, wi