e; sen hay l&aacute; chuá»‘i, l&aacute; dong. NgÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n b&aacute;nh thÆ°á»�ng Ä‘á»™i th&uacute;ng b&aacute;nh tr&ecirc;n Ä‘áº§u, di dáº¡o b&aacute;n tr&ecirc;n phá»‘ phÆ°á»�ng H&agrave; Ná»™i. Khi gáº·p ngÆ°á»�i mua, ngÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n h&agrave;ng sáº½ háº¡ th&uacute;ng xuá»‘ng, láº§n giá»Ÿ tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n má»�ng, t&aacute;ch tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh sao l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n khá»�i bá»‹ r&aacute;ch. Tr&ecirc;n máº·t l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘iá»ƒm nhá»¯ng cá»�ng h&agrave;nh l&aacute; m&agrave;u v&agrave;ng, n&acirc;u Ä‘&atilde; Ä‘Æ°á»£c phi qua tr&ecirc;n cháº£o. Má»—i lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘&oacute; sáº½ Ä‘Æ°á»£c sáº¯p xáº¿p gá»�n láº¡i tr&ecirc;n Ä‘Ä©a, láº§n lÆ°á»£t tá»«ng miáº¿ng b&aacute;nh má»™t Ä‘Æ°á»£c Ä‘áº·t cáº¡nh nhau. Sau Ä‘&oacute;, vá»›i má»™t nh&aacute;t k&eacute;o, táº¥t cáº£ c&aacute;c l&aacute; b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n Ä‘Æ°á»£c cáº¯t Ä‘&ocirc;i. C&ocirc;ng viá»‡c tiáº¿p theo l&agrave; nháº¥c má»™t ná»­a Ä‘áº§u b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n má»›i cáº¯t Ä‘&oacute;, Ä‘áº·t l&ecirc;n tr&ecirc;n ná»­a kia Ä‘á»ƒ ngÆ°á»�i thÆ°á»Ÿng thá»©c c&oacute; thá»ƒ nh&igrave;n tháº¥y r&otilde; tá»«ng lá»›p b&aacute;nh cuá»‘n tr&aacute;ng má»�ng nhÆ° giáº¥y. B&aacute;nh Ä‘Æ°á»£c Äƒn vá»›i thá»© nÆ°á»›c cháº¥m Ä‘áº·c trÆ°ng cho tá»«ng ngÆ°á»�i b&aacute;n b&aacute;nh ri&ecirc;ng, c&oacute; thá»ƒ Äƒn k&egrave;m cháº£ quáº¿, gi&ograve; lá»¥a hoáº·c Ä‘áº­u r&aacute;n v&agrave; rau m&ugrave;i.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 16:09:18',1,'admin'),(84,25,7,'Phá»Ÿ&nbsp;','','pho','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Phá»Ÿ (Vietnamese pronunciation: often written pho in Australia, New Zealand, United Kingdom, and United States where it is typically pronounced /ËˆfÊŒ/[1]) is a Vietnamese noodle soup, usually served with beef (pho bo) or chicken (pho ga).[2] The soup includes noodles made from rice and is often served with basil, lime, bean sprouts, and peppers that are added to the soup by the consumer.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The origin of phá»Ÿ is uncertain, and is mostly culled from oral histories. The specific place of origin appears to be southwest of Hanoi in Nam Dinh province, believed to harbor both a Chinese and French connection. The noodles comes from China, and the broth appears to be French in origin, making use of bones and lesser cuts of beef. Some have suggested that phá»Ÿ is derived from pot au feu, the classic French beef stew. Phá»Ÿ did not become popular in South Vietnam until the mid-1950s.[3] Linguistically, however, this is unlikely. In the Vietnamese language, the word phá»Ÿ carries a non-flat category, whereas most French loanwords carry a flat tone, sáº¯c or náº·ng tone, depending on the end consonant except the loanwords are ended with -t, -p, -c, -ch consonants. Phá»Ÿ does not match this rule.[6]<br />a plain Cantonese Hofan</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79c58b72_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>a plain Cantonese Hofan</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Some observers[4] believe phá»Ÿ may come from the Cantonese rice vermicelli Hofan (æ²³ç²‰) which are interchangeably abbreviated as either fan2[7](ç²‰, pháº¥n in Tá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t) or Ho2[8](æ²³, H&agrave; inTá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t ), the two sounds giving the name \"phá»Ÿ\".[4] Both fan and pho refer to the same rice noodles found in Vietnam and Guangdong, China, suggesting that rice noodles may have been brought to Vietnam by Cantonese immigrants from the Guangdong province in the early 20th century. The noodles are cooked identically in both places, and are often seasoned using fish sauce, garnished with bean sprouts, and served with meat balls and sliced beef. Vietnamese phá»Ÿ, however, is further garnished with fresh mint, cilantro, basil, bean sprouts, limes, sliced chili peppers and sliced raw beef[9]; this is especially true of Saigon-style phá»Ÿ. Furthermore, the broth of phá»Ÿ is made of beef bones and fresh onion, whereas the Cantonese broth of fan is made of dried flatfish and other seafood. In some regional varieties, the Vietnamese broth may also have a mildly sweet flavour from Asian yellow rock sugar, but the Cantonese version is not.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Vietnamese phá»Ÿ noodle soup with sliced rare beef and well done beef brisket<br />Possibly the earliest reference to phá»Ÿ in English was in the book Recipes of All Nations edited by Countess Morphy in 1935. In the book, phá»Ÿ is described as \"an Annamese soup held in high esteem...made with beef, a veal bone, onions, a bayleaf, salt, and pepper, and a small teaspoon of nuoc-man.\"[citation needed]<br /><br />With the Vietnam war and the victory of the Viet Cong, phá»Ÿ was brought to many countries by Vietnamese refugees fleeing Vietnam from the 1970s onwards. It is especially popular in large cities with substantial Vietnamese populations and enclaves such as Paris in France, the West Coast of Canada[10], the East and West Coast of the United States, Sydney and Melbourne of Australia, and Hong Kong.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79d3600b_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Typical garnishes for phá»Ÿ: cilantro, basil, lime, bean sprouts and onions.</em></p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 16:16:37',1,'admin'),(85,25,7,'Phá»Ÿ&nbsp;','','pho','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Phá»Ÿ (Vietnamese pronunciation: often written pho in Australia, New Zealand, United Kingdom, and United States where it is typically pronounced /ËˆfÊŒ/) is a Vietnamese noodle soup, usually served with beef (pho bo) or chicken (pho ga). The soup includes noodles made from rice and is often served with basil, lime, bean sprouts, and peppers that are added to the soup by the consumer.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The origin of phá»Ÿ is uncertain, and is mostly culled from oral histories. The specific place of origin appears to be southwest of Hanoi in Nam Dinh province, believed to harbor both a Chinese and French connection. The noodles comes from China, and the broth appears to be French in origin, making use of bones and lesser cuts of beef. Some have suggested that phá»Ÿ is derived from pot au feu, the classic French beef stew. Phá»Ÿ did not become popular in South Vietnam until the mid-1950s. Linguistically, however, this is unlikely. In the Vietnamese language, the word phá»Ÿ carries a non-flat category, whereas most French loanwords carry a flat tone, sáº¯c or náº·ng tone, depending on the end consonant except the loanwords are ended with -t, -p, -c, -ch consonants. Phá»Ÿ does not match this rule.<br />a plain Cantonese Hofan</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79c58b72_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>a plain Cantonese Hofan</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Some observers believe phá»Ÿ may come from the Cantonese rice vermicelli Hofan (æ²³ç²‰) which are interchangeably abbreviated as either fan2(ç²‰, pháº¥n in Tá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t) or Ho2(æ²³, H&agrave; inTá»± H&aacute;n Viá»‡t ), the two sounds giving the name \"phá»Ÿ\".Both fan and pho refer to the same rice noodles found in Vietnam and Guangdong, China, suggesting that rice noodles may have been brought to Vietnam by Cantonese immigrants from the Guangdong province in the early 20th century. The noodles are cooked identically in both places, and are often seasoned using fish sauce, garnished with bean sprouts, and served with meat balls and sliced beef. Vietnamese phá»Ÿ, however, is further garnished with fresh mint, cilantro, basil, bean sprouts, limes, sliced chili peppers and sliced raw beef[9]; this is especially true of Saigon-style phá»Ÿ. Furthermore, the broth of phá»Ÿ is made of beef bones and fresh onion, whereas the Cantonese broth of fan is made of dried flatfish and other seafood. In some regional varieties, the Vietnamese broth may also have a mildly sweet flavour from Asian yellow rock sugar, but the Cantonese version is not.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Vietnamese phá»Ÿ noodle soup with sliced rare beef and well done beef brisket<br />Possibly the earliest reference to phá»Ÿ in English was in the book Recipes of All Nations edited by Countess Morphy in 1935. In the book, phá»Ÿ is described as \"an Annamese soup held in high esteem...made with beef, a veal bone, onions, a bayleaf, salt, and pepper, and a small teaspoon of nuoc-man.\"<br /><br />With the Vietnam war and the victory of the Viet Cong, phá»Ÿ was brought to many countries by Vietnamese refugees fleeing Vietnam from the 1970s onwards. It is especially popular in large cities with substantial Vietnamese populations and enclaves such as Paris in France, the West Coast of Canada[10], the East and West Coast of the United States, Sydney and Melbourne of Australia, and Hong Kong.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cc79d3600b_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Typical garnishes for phá»Ÿ: cilantro, basil, lime, bean sprouts and onions.</em></p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 16:18:28',1,'admin'),(86,26,18,'Phá»Ÿ&nbsp;','','pho','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Phá»Ÿ l&agrave; má»™t m&oacute;n Äƒn truyá»�n thá»‘ng cá»§a Viá»‡t Nam, cÅ©ng c&oacute; thá»ƒ xem l&agrave; má»™t trong nhá»¯ng m&oacute;n Äƒn Ä‘áº·c trÆ°ng nháº¥t cho áº©m thá»±c Viá»‡t Nam.</p>','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Th&agrave;nh pháº§n ch&iacute;nh cá»§a phá»Ÿ l&agrave; b&aacute;nh phá»Ÿ v&agrave; nÆ°á»›c d&ugrave;ng (hay nÆ°á»›c l&egrave;o theo c&aacute;ch gá»�i miá»�n Nam) c&ugrave;ng vá»›i thá»‹t b&ograve; hoáº·c g&agrave; cáº¯t l&aacute;t má»�ng. Ngo&agrave;