3.056 m&sup2;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ng&agrave;nh h&agrave;ng kinh doanh chá»§ yáº¿u: Quáº§n &aacute;o, váº£i sá»£i, giáº§y d&eacute;p, thá»�i trang, h&agrave;ng thá»§ c&ocirc;ng má»¹ nghá»‡, thá»±c pháº©m tÆ°Æ¡i sá»‘ng, tr&aacute;i c&acirc;y, hoa tÆ°Æ¡i.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ce021481af_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Chá»£ Báº¿n Th&agrave;nh<br /></em></p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 18:17:33',1,'admin'),(117,35,2,'BÃ¡nh Ä‘Ãºc','','banh-duc','<p>B&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a term used to refer to two different varieties of Vietnamese b&aacute;nh, or cake.</p>','<h2>Northern Vietnamese version</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In northern Vietnam, b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a cake made from either non-glutinous rice flour or corn flour. It is white in color and has a soft texture and mild flavour.photo It is typically garnished with savory ingredients such as ground pork, t&ocirc;m cháº¥y (grilled ground shrimp),photo fried onions, sesame seeds, salt, peanuts, lime juice, and soy sauce or fish sauce.photo Although it may be eaten on its own, it may also be served hot, accompanied by steamed meat or mushrooms.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cdd066d361_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>A bowl of northern Vietnamese b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c thá»‹t (b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c with ground pork and fish sauce)</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is available at small stalls and is eaten throughout the day.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><span id=\"Southern_Vietnamese_version\" class=\"mw-headline\">Southern Vietnamese version</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cdc71e1d42_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>A plate of southern Vietnamese b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c colored with Pandanus amaryllifolius leaf extract, and topped with sweetened coconut milk and sesame seeds</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In southern Vietnam, b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a dessert made from non-glutinous rice flour. It takes the form of gelatinous blocks that are often colored green by the addition of Pandanus amaryllifolius leaf extract. It is cooked by boiling the ingredients and allowing them to cool, solidifying into a jelly-like sheetphoto that is then cut into blocks.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 18:20:23',1,'admin'),(118,35,2,'BÃ¡nh Ä‘Ãºc','','banh-duc','<p>B&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a term used to refer to two different varieties of Vietnamese b&aacute;nh, or cake.</p>','<h2>Northern Vietnamese version</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In northern Vietnam, b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a cake made from either non-glutinous rice flour or corn flour. It is white in color and has a soft texture and mild flavour.photo It is typically garnished with savory ingredients such as ground pork, t&ocirc;m cháº¥y (grilled ground shrimp),photo fried onions, sesame seeds, salt, peanuts, lime juice, and soy sauce or fish sauce.photo Although it may be eaten on its own, it may also be served hot, accompanied by steamed meat or mushrooms.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cdd066d361_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>A bowl of northern Vietnamese b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c thá»‹t (b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c with ground pork and fish sauce)</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">B&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is available at small stalls and is eaten throughout the day.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><span id=\"Southern_Vietnamese_version\" class=\"mw-headline\">Southern Vietnamese version</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7cdc71e1d42_crop.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>A plate of southern Vietnamese b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c colored with Pandanus amaryllifolius leaf extract, and topped with sweetened coconut milk and sesame seeds</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In southern Vietnam, b&aacute;nh Ä‘&uacute;c is a dessert made from non-glutinous rice flour. It takes the form of gelatinous blocks that are often colored green by the addition of Pandanus amaryllifolius leaf extract. It is cooked by boiling the ingredients and allowing them to cool, solidifying into a jelly-like sheetphoto that is then cut into blocks.</p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 18:20:23',1,'admin'),(119,38,12,'Mid-Autumn Festival','','mid-autumn-festival','<p>The Mid-Autumn Festival, also known as the Moon Festival, Zhongqiu Festival, or in Chinese, Zhongqiujie, or in Vietnamese \"Táº¿t Trung Thu\", is a popular harvest festival celebrated by Chinese and Vietnamese people, dating back over 3,000 years to moon worship in China\'s Shang Dynasty.</p>','<p>The Mid-Autumn Festival is held on the 15th day of the eighth month in the Chinese calendar, which is usually around late September or early October in the Gregorian calendar. It is a date that parallels the autumnal equinox of the solar calendar, when the moon is supposedly at its fullest and roundest. The traditional food of this festival is the mooncake, of which there are many different varieties.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ce033ae1f6_medium.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Mid-Autumn Festival at the Botanical Garden, Montreal</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p>The Mid-Autumn Festival is one of the few most important holidays in the Chinese calendar, the others being Chinese New Year and Winter Solstice, and is a legal holiday in several countries. Farmers celebrate the end of the summer harvesting season on this date. Traditionally on this day, Chinese family members and friends will gather to admire the bright mid-autumn harvest moon, and eat moon cakes and pomelos under the moon together.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ce032b90af_medium.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Mid-Autumn Festival celebrations in Victoria Park, Hong Kong</em></p>','Wikipedia','','2010-08-31 18:23:15',1,'admin'),(120,40,24,'Táº¿t Trung thu','','tet-trung-thu','<p>Táº¿t Trung Thu theo &acirc;m lá»‹ch l&agrave; ng&agrave;y ráº±m th&aacute;ng 8 háº±ng nÄƒm. Ä�&acirc;y l&agrave; ng&agrave;y táº¿t cá»§a tráº» em, c&ograve;n Ä‘Æ°á»£c gá»�i l&agrave; \"Táº¿t tr&ocirc;ng TrÄƒng\" hay Táº¿t Thiáº¿u nhi, Táº¿t Nhi Ä‘á»“ng.</p>','<p>Tráº» em ráº¥t mong Ä‘á»£i Ä‘Æ°á»£c Ä‘&oacute;n táº¿t n&agrave;y v&igrave; thÆ°á»�ng Ä‘Æ°á»£c ngÆ°á»�i lá»›n táº·ng Ä‘á»“ chÆ¡i, thÆ°á»�ng l&agrave; Ä‘&egrave;n &ocirc;ng sao, máº·t náº¡, Ä‘&egrave;n k&eacute;o qu&acirc;n, s&uacute;ng phun nÆ°á»›c... rá»“i b&aacute;nh nÆ°á»›ng, b&aacute;nh dáº»o. V&agrave;o ng&agrave;y táº¿t n&agrave;y, ngÆ°á»�i ta tá»• chá»©c b&agrave;y cá»—, tr&ocirc;ng trÄƒng. Thá»�i Ä‘iá»ƒm trÄƒng l&ecirc;n cao, tráº» em sáº½ vá»«a m&uacute;a h&aacute;t vá»«a ngáº¯m trÄƒng ph&aacute; cá»—. á»ž má»™t sá»‘ nÆ¡i ngÆ°á»�i ta c&ograve;n tá»• chá»©c m&uacute;a l&acirc;n, m&uacute;a sÆ° tá»­, m&uacute;a rá»“ng Ä‘á»ƒ c&aacute;c em vui chÆ¡i thoáº£ th&iacute;c